FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - THAILAND
*******************************
A ProMED-mail post
Date: Wed, 24 Sep. 1997
From: Sharon Rose <fasstudy@fas.org>
Source: OIE Disease Information, Vol 10, No 42

The following is the text of a fax received on 21 October 1997 from Dr
Vichitr Sukhapesna, Deputy Director General, Department of Livestock
Development, Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives, Bangkok.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 26 September 1997.
Estimated date of first infection: 25 September 1997.
Description of affected population: cattle sourced from accredited farm in
Nakhonsawan province for exportation to Malaysia.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species susceptible cases deaths destroyed slaughtered
bov 292 2 0 2 0
Diagnosis: officers from Animal Quarantine at port of exit, Department of
Livestock Development (Padang Besar, Songkhla province, Thailand) together
with officers from Animal Quarantine at port of entry, Department of
Veterinary Services (Malaysia) detected FMD lesions in two bovines.
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Foot and Mouth Disease Diagnostic
Centre, Nakhonratchsima province.
B. Diagnostic tests used: ELISA antigen method.
C. Causal agent: FMD virus type A.
Source of agent / origin of infection: tracing back carried out to find out
the true sources of infection.
Control measures during reporting period:
The total of 292 head of cattle were refused entry into Malaysia. The 2
infected animals were destroyed on 28 September 1997. The rest of the
animals are being isolated for one month at Padang Besar Check Point before
being sent for slaughter for local consumption. The farm of origin is
suspended for export to Malaysia. Thorough cleansing and disinfection of
the farm were carried out. Sentinel animals have since been placed in the
farm for a period of one month.
--
Sharon Rose
FAS ProMED/AHEAD Associate
<fasstudy@fas.org>
